{"key":"processedPost-10740541","value":{"id":10740541,"first":9946883,"last":10740541,"when":1248584669,"utime":"07/26/09 08:04 AM","cleanedPost":"The only problem with foil being left on is if it's crimped down tight.&nbsp; It doesn't stop gas exchange, but it can tend to allow the dry verm barrier or other filter to get damp, and a damp filter will lead to contamination.&nbsp; I really noticed this a lot with synthetic filter disks, especially if they were on the inside, such as with plastic lids.&nbsp; I was getting about a ten percent bacterial contamination rate, which is completely unacceptable.&nbsp; By removing the foil and always using metal lids with the filter on top where it stays dry, the problem disappeared.&nbsp; As hyphae said, I'm sure if it's just sitting there loosely, it won't hurt anything.&nbsp; I reuse the foil over and over again, so always write on the glass surface of the jars where it comes off easily between uses.<br />RR"}}